The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Metro | The City Diary
                                                                                                                         3                                                                                      The City Diary
                Violence broke out on Karaya Road after a state bus ran over a 36-year-old woman, Yasmin Begum, on Rifle Range Road on Wednesday night. The woman lost her right leg. Residents attacked a police team from Karaya police station, injuring at least six cops, when it arrived on the spot. Officers from three nearby police stations fired several rounds of tear gas shells and lathicharged the mob in an attempt to control the situation.    Trouble broke out at the Kanchrapara municipality auditorium on Wednesday after alleged Trinamul Congress activists beat up several government employees who had turned up at a meeting called by the state election commission. Ajay Paul, the sub-divisional officer of Barrackpore, said the activists claimed that many of the government employees at the meeting were biased in favour of the CPM. The SDO later lodged a complaint with Bijpur police station.    A small fire broke out on the third floor of Calcutta International School around 10am on Wednesday. The flames, which originated from an air-conditioner, were doused within minutes. Principal Anuradha Das said the students were evacuated immediately. The school will remain closed on Thursday for repairs.    Mausumi Alam, in her 30s, was admitted to National Medical College and Hospital with a slit throat on Monday afternoon. Mausumis husband Noor Alam, also in his 30s, rushed to their Karaya home after he heard his wife groaning over the phone. Police said Noor, an employee of the public health engineering department, found Mausumi lying injured in the house.    Ujjwal Ghosh, 26, a Barasat resident, was injured in the head after being knocked down by a bus on Jessore Road around 11.30am on Wednesday. Residents smashed a glass window of the bus and demonstrated till police reached the spot. Ghosh was taken to RG Kar hospital.    South Calcutta Law College will get a new campus on a 10-cottah plot in Kasba, principal Debashis Chattopadhyay said on Wednesday. The Calcutta Municipal Corporation has sanctioned the plan.    The Calcutta leg of the Queens Baton Relay ushering in the Delhi Commonwealth Games  will take place on August 1, chief secretary Ardhendu Sen said at Writers Buildings on Wednesday. The baton will then travel through the districts.    Around 50 people blocked DC Dey Road in Tangra late on Tuesday to protest the arrest of a local youth, Md Azad. Police said a drunk Azad was creating a ruckus when he was arrested. The blockade was withdrawn after senior police officers intervened.    CESC will be allowed to lay underground cables that will require digging of roads for a month. The decision was taken at a meeting between CESC and Calcutta Municipal Corporation officials on Wednesday.     A family, travelling to Calcutta from Ranchi, was robbed of cash and jewellery worth Rs 3.5 lakh on board the Hatia-Howrah Express on Tuesday night. The family has lodged a complaint with the Howrah GRP.            
